• Editor's note: This is a developing story. We will bring you updates as more information becomes available. JOHANNESBURG – The R558 has been opened and calm has returned to Ennerdale following violence by protesters early on Thursday morning. There is however a heavy police presence in the area. Acting Police Commissioner Khomotso Phahlane was in the area speaking to journalists, he called for local authorities to play their part in resolving the communities issues. Police were also stationed at the Mid Ennerdale Primary School where it was rumoured that protesters wanted to burn down the school. Parents gathered outside Mid #Ennerdale Primary School following rumours that protesters plan to burn the school. #HousingProtest pic.twitter.com/IvEhOFHieJ The Ennerdale Stakeholders Association has distanced itself from violence that erupted and says criminals are to blame for clashes with police. Violence flared in the area and police have had to use teargas to disperse a protesting crowd. Police removing rocks and burning tyre on James Street. #HousingProtest #EnnerdaleProtest pic.twitter.com/aHid5Z8Kfw Johannesburg Metro Police Department (JMPD) spokesman Chief Superintendent Wayne Minnaar said motorists should avoid the intersection between Provincial and James roads. Traffic affected on R557 due to #EnnerdaleProtest pic.twitter.com/ctNjkPxm3F #Ennerdale resident - We are tired of being a mockery. #EnnerdaleProtest pic.twitter.com/jglvlKCjcr “It's not safe for motorists to drive on that intersection as there are stones being thrown. The roads in Ennerdale have also been barricaded.” READ: Protests erupt in Ennerdale Minnaar said the South African Police Service and JMPD were on scene to monitor the situation. Residents took to the streets on Tuesday to protest against the lack of housing in the area. There were reports of violence and clashes with police. The residents, had, however, agreed to suspend the protests after they had a meeting with Johannesburg Council S